1
00:00:49,091 --> 00:00:52,129
I start with a question,
as a filmmaker and a storyteller,

2
00:00:52,219 --> 00:00:55,007
how should this story tell itself?

3
00:00:55,097 --> 00:00:57,429
Because there's different strategies
that are available.

4
00:00:57,516 --> 00:00:59,553
And what attracted me
to Stuart Beattie's screenplay

5
00:00:59,643 --> 00:01:03,557
was the notion that it all happens
in a very short time frame,

6
00:01:03,647 --> 00:01:06,890
meaning that it's like the third act
of a traditional drama

7
00:01:06,984 --> 00:01:10,234
and you're making a whole
motion picture about only the third act.

8
00:01:11,196 --> 00:01:13,066
One of the big reasons
I wanted to make the film

9
00:01:13,156 --> 00:01:15,523
was that we're seeing fractions,
or fractals...

10
00:01:15,617 --> 00:01:18,325
We're seeing a fraction
that represents the whole,

11
00:01:18,412 --> 00:01:23,782
and only what you need to know
is what you're seeing.

12
00:01:23,875 --> 00:01:26,913
And it doesn't go backward in time

13
00:01:27,004 --> 00:01:29,211
or give you exposition
about other parts of their lives.

14
00:01:29,298 --> 00:01:31,756
They don't really talk
about themselves that much.

15
00:01:31,842 --> 00:01:35,051
So in the beginning,
I wanted to enter this scene,

16
00:01:35,137 --> 00:01:38,004
or enter these activities,
with kind of a torn edge.

17
00:01:38,974 --> 00:01:40,931
So we just see Vincent in LAX.

18
00:01:41,018 --> 00:01:44,977
We hear a plane land, Vincent's in LAX.
He meets somebody who's foreign

19
00:01:45,063 --> 00:01:46,770
and that's all you need to know
is that he's foreign.

20
00:01:46,857 --> 00:01:49,519
He's got a South London,
working-class accent.

21
00:01:51,486 --> 00:01:53,944
This accidental bumping
into each other, you realise,

22
00:01:54,031 --> 00:01:56,693
if I've done my job correctly,
is not really accidental.

23
00:01:56,783 --> 00:01:59,901
It's premeditated,
and a briefcase has been exchanged,

24
00:01:59,995 --> 00:02:02,032
so that whatever it is
that Vincent's here to do,

25
00:02:02,122 --> 00:02:04,614
you know only the few things
you need to know,

26
00:02:04,708 --> 00:02:07,666
which is that there was
a premeditated plan to it,

27
00:02:07,753 --> 00:02:09,243
it's secretive,

28
00:02:09,338 --> 00:02:11,750
and it involves people
from foreign places.

29
00:02:12,758 --> 00:02:16,877
And then we enter the domain of Max,
but we don't know what it is.

30
00:02:16,970 --> 00:02:19,803
First, there's abstract pieces
of things, and then we realise

31
00:02:19,890 --> 00:02:22,382
those abstract pieces of things
are, in fact, cars

32
00:02:22,476 --> 00:02:26,435
and that the cars are cabs and that
there's drivers waiting to go on a shift.

33
00:02:26,521 --> 00:02:30,310
And what I'm trying to direct
the attention to is that Max

34
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:35,520
IS very obsessive
about making this environment

35
00:02:35,614 --> 00:02:38,527
of the interior of his cab
clean and perfect

36
00:02:38,617 --> 00:02:41,951
and that he has a picture
that has some significance to him,

37
00:02:42,037 --> 00:02:44,449
'cause he very carefully
mounts it on his visor,

38
00:02:44,539 --> 00:02:48,077
and that he closes out chaos,
makes chaos go away.

39
00:02:53,882 --> 00:02:57,500
This mural that we put outside the cab

40
00:02:57,594 --> 00:03:00,256
comes from Estrada Courts,
which is in East LA,

41
00:03:00,347 --> 00:03:05,342
and there's a spectacular tradition
in Los Angeles of mural painting

42
00:03:05,435 --> 00:03:08,143
that's Hispanic, derives from Mexico.

43
00:03:08,230 --> 00:03:11,188
And this is... It was painted in '74.
The painter's anonymous,

44
00:03:11,274 --> 00:03:13,356
and he never finished it.
The vaquero doesn't have a head,

45
00:03:13,443 --> 00:03:15,480
and for some reason
that I can't put my finger on,

46
00:03:15,570 --> 00:03:18,858
it just really felt like it fit
into the vision of here's Max

47
00:03:18,949 --> 00:03:22,408
launching out of the cab depot
onto the streets of Los Angeles

48
00:03:22,494 --> 00:03:25,532
in late afternoon, on a shift
that probably began about 4:00.

49
00:03:27,457 --> 00:03:31,291
Cab driver described to me as
folks who get in the back seat

50
00:03:31,378 --> 00:03:34,791
are kind of like a radio
with a random wonder bar.

51
00:03:34,881 --> 00:03:37,623
You never know what station
you're gonna land on,

52
00:03:37,718 --> 00:03:40,927
and so you never know
who's gonna wind up in the back seat.

53
00:03:42,264 --> 00:03:44,384
There's a lot of aerial shots
in the picture,

54
00:03:44,474 --> 00:03:48,718
and they're shot with a Wescam
mount, which is amazingly steady.

55
00:03:48,812 --> 00:03:52,555
This is a gas station just off
the Santa Monica Freeway

56
00:03:52,649 --> 00:03:59,021
after the sun has set, and the light
in LA has this amazing red quality,

57
00:03:59,114 --> 00:04:00,855
red-yellow quality to it.

58
00:04:00,949 --> 00:04:04,533
And the mural of the products for sale

59
00:04:04,619 --> 00:04:08,704
in the tienda is taken off
a tienda in East LA.

60
00:04:08,790 --> 00:04:11,828
The fractions of LA
and how diverse LA is,

61
00:04:11,918 --> 00:04:14,535
and diverse not in...
I grew up in Chicago.

62
00:04:14,629 --> 00:04:17,212
Not in a Chicago or East Coast
or New York way,

63
00:04:17,299 --> 00:04:21,759
but diverse in a Pac-Rim, Hispanic,
Los Angeles way

64
00:04:21,845 --> 00:04:25,258
are part of the intent of,
again, the opening of the film,

65
00:04:25,348 --> 00:04:27,760
Max's world,
and the world of Los Angeles.

66
00:04:27,851 --> 00:04:31,344
Now, this guy here, his real name,
the actor's name is Manny Urrego,

67
00:04:31,438 --> 00:04:35,853
and he was a limo driver.
In working out every detail,

68
00:04:35,942 --> 00:04:38,605
the most important details
of Max's life as a cab driver

69
00:04:38,695 --> 00:04:41,062
and the work we did
in preproduction with Jamie,

70
00:04:41,156 --> 00:04:44,945
one of the key things we did
was make complete

71
00:04:45,035 --> 00:04:48,994
Max's business plan
for having a limo company,

72
00:04:49,080 --> 00:04:54,041
and consequently,
Manny provided spreadsheets,

73
00:04:54,127 --> 00:04:59,793
a whole business plan, complete
with depreciation, overhead, salaries.

74
00:05:01,468 --> 00:05:06,588
Annie is played by Jada Pinkett Smith,
who I worked with in Al

75
00:05:06,681 --> 00:05:08,843
When Jada gets in the cab...

76
00:05:08,934 --> 00:05:11,517
This is one of the first sequences
we shot,

77
00:05:11,603 --> 00:05:16,564
and we were using the Sony F900
high-definition video camera.

78
00:05:16,650 --> 00:05:19,859
If we were shooting film,
you wouldn't see any definition

79
00:05:19,945 --> 00:05:24,860
of the images behind them.
And you wouldn't have this feeling

80
00:05:24,950 --> 00:05:30,036
of the low light levels that make me
feel that we're actually in a cab.

81
00:05:45,220 --> 00:05:48,383
The picture was originally written
for New York City.

82
00:05:49,516 --> 00:05:52,804
And my interest in shooting
a motion picture that took place at night

83
00:05:52,894 --> 00:05:55,761
in Los Angeles
in a compressed period of time

84
00:05:55,856 --> 00:05:59,394
predates my getting my hands
on the Collateral script,

85
00:05:59,484 --> 00:06:02,084
which was given to me
by Walter Parkes at DreamWorks.

86
00:06:04,739 --> 00:06:07,110
And it's written by Stuart Beattie.
It's an excellent script,

87
00:06:07,200 --> 00:06:10,909
but it was written about
the Russian Mafia and New York City.

88
00:06:10,996 --> 00:06:15,206
And my interest was immediately
to transpose all of that

89
00:06:15,292 --> 00:06:21,459
into not just LA as a location, but LA
with its unique, diverse population.

90
00:06:21,548 --> 00:06:23,459
And the way it seems to be organized,

91
00:06:23,550 --> 00:06:26,633
where there are almost, like,
sites or domains

92
00:06:29,514 --> 00:06:33,678
that you travel to. The ethnic richness

93
00:06:33,768 --> 00:06:37,056
and the sense of place in LA

94
00:06:37,147 --> 00:06:39,104
is not immediately apparent
off the freeways.

95
00:06:39,190 --> 00:06:40,976
You have to go to it.

96
00:06:46,448 --> 00:06:52,285
And then in putting together the film,
again, as the storyteller,

97
00:06:52,370 --> 00:06:56,034
the first thing I'm looking for is,
who are these people?

98
00:06:56,124 --> 00:06:58,957
Who is Max? Who is Vincent?
Who are these characters?

99
00:07:02,213 --> 00:07:04,705
What's their history?
Where did Vincent come from?

100
00:07:04,799 --> 00:07:09,544
How did Vincent get made into
the Vincent who shows up in LA,

101
00:07:09,638 --> 00:07:11,174
late afternoon

102
00:07:12,474 --> 00:07:14,056
on this one day?

103
00:07:14,809 --> 00:07:16,846
Where did Max come from?

104
00:07:16,937 --> 00:07:20,931
Some of the answers to this
that, as the director,

105
00:07:21,024 --> 00:07:23,857
that I build in building the characters

106
00:07:24,986 --> 00:07:27,353
and in working with the actors
in preproduction

107
00:07:27,447 --> 00:07:31,315
and in forming the character
of Vincent with Tom

108
00:07:31,409 --> 00:07:34,868
and Max with Jamie had to do with

109
00:07:38,083 --> 00:07:40,541
their histories, where they came from.

110
00:07:40,627 --> 00:07:43,836
In fact, the back-story
of Tom and the film

111
00:07:43,922 --> 00:07:49,042
was that in the offshore world
of narco-trafficking cartels,

112
00:07:51,346 --> 00:07:53,758
they have the budgets
to buy the best, and they do.

113
00:07:53,848 --> 00:07:55,805
Particularly since the end
of the Cold War went on,

114
00:07:55,892 --> 00:07:58,224
that labour market has become available.

115
00:07:58,311 --> 00:08:03,932
People who are ex-KGB, ex-Stasi,
as well as Brits and Americans

116
00:08:04,025 --> 00:08:06,938
from special forces, Israelis.

117
00:08:07,696 --> 00:08:11,109
And these cartels also have
the best of computer technicians,

118
00:08:11,199 --> 00:08:15,113
signal-intercept capabilities
to run sophisticated counter-intel,

119
00:08:15,203 --> 00:08:18,491
as well as attorneys
and private investigators to discover

120
00:08:18,581 --> 00:08:21,202
if there's any operations
against them or whether or not

121
00:08:21,292 --> 00:08:24,785
there's a Department of Justice
investigation or a DEA investigation

122
00:08:24,879 --> 00:08:27,500
or any indictments pending
against them in the United States.

123
00:08:27,590 --> 00:08:29,706
And that's exactly what's happened here.

124
00:08:33,763 --> 00:08:35,925
The group that's hired Vincent
has found out

125
00:08:36,016 --> 00:08:38,887
that there are pending indictments
and that an assistant U.S. attorney,

126
00:08:38,977 --> 00:08:43,596
played by Jada, is, in fact, about
to indict, in a grand-jury hearing

127
00:08:43,690 --> 00:08:46,728
that's supposed to begin
tomorrow morning, certain figures.

128
00:08:46,818 --> 00:08:49,355
And they have had
private investigators working,

129
00:08:49,446 --> 00:08:52,859
and they've discovered the identities
of five key witnesses

130
00:08:52,949 --> 00:08:55,195
and have spent the last three
or four months working up

131
00:08:55,285 --> 00:08:58,027
an operation to kill these witnesses.

132
00:08:58,121 --> 00:08:59,782
And tonight's the night.

133
00:09:00,373 --> 00:09:02,911
Max and Annie, who have just met
in this cab, Max doesn't even know

134
00:09:03,001 --> 00:09:05,709
she's a prosecutor yet,
are completely unaware of this.

135
00:09:06,713 --> 00:09:11,048
I wanted to form characters who were
absolute strangers to each other

136
00:09:11,134 --> 00:09:16,755
and constituted opposites to each other
in every conceivable way that I could,

137
00:09:16,848 --> 00:09:20,591
because they're about to be
thrown together into this cab.

138
00:09:22,145 --> 00:09:24,891
One of the big things
that appealed to me about this film

139
00:09:24,981 --> 00:09:30,442
is to tell a story the way
this story tells itself,

140
00:09:30,528 --> 00:09:33,941
which is that since we're only
in these 10 hours,

141
00:09:34,032 --> 00:09:37,525
we're only seeing
a small fraction of a whole life.

142
00:09:37,619 --> 00:09:41,112
And since we're only in the 10 hours,
the challenge is,

143
00:09:41,206 --> 00:09:45,791
"Can I design those fractions
so that they become glimpses,

144
00:09:45,877 --> 00:09:48,164
“ "that you kind of sense the person?"

145
00:09:48,379 --> 00:09:50,086
To do that, one has to invent

146
00:09:50,173 --> 00:09:53,256
the history of Vincent,
the history of Max,

147
00:09:53,343 --> 00:09:58,008
and then choose those details
to put into the 10 hours of tonight.

148
00:09:58,098 --> 00:10:02,717
The way Max dresses or the kind of
self-deceptive attitude he has

149
00:10:02,811 --> 00:10:05,018
when he talks about a limo company.

150
00:10:05,105 --> 00:10:06,470
The film doesn't do

151
00:10:06,564 --> 00:10:11,604
what a life experience of these 10 hours
also would not do,

152
00:10:11,694 --> 00:10:16,313
which is to have exposition
or to travel backwards in time

153
00:10:16,407 --> 00:10:19,115
via flashbacks or any of those
other devices,

154
00:10:19,202 --> 00:10:22,285
but instead just to keep us
immediate into this present,

155
00:10:22,372 --> 00:10:26,161
and yet to have a greater degree
of knowingness about their lives.

156
00:10:32,173 --> 00:10:38,135
Max is averse to impulsive action.
He has planned to perfection

157
00:10:38,221 --> 00:10:40,842
this business plan, in which
he's gonna set up a limo company.

158
00:10:40,932 --> 00:10:42,764
He's been doing it for 12 years.

159
00:10:42,851 --> 00:10:46,389
Now, one of the hardest things
for an actor to play is indecision.

160
00:10:46,479 --> 00:10:52,020
That in-between state means that...
That's exactly what Max is.

161
00:10:52,110 --> 00:10:55,648
He's a man who has big dreams
and has realised none of them.

162
00:10:55,738 --> 00:10:56,733
So for Jamie to play this,

163
00:10:56,823 --> 00:11:01,943
it means that he must generate
the object of Max's desire,

164
00:11:02,036 --> 00:11:06,530
really experience it and feel it,
and then invent what impedes him

165
00:11:06,624 --> 00:11:11,164
from actualising it so that he exists
in that kind of twilight zone

166
00:11:11,254 --> 00:11:14,121
of potential and frustration.

167
00:11:14,215 --> 00:11:18,254
And in this case,
it all becomes personified by Annie,

168
00:11:18,344 --> 00:11:20,676
with whom he has this stunning rapport,

169
00:11:20,763 --> 00:11:24,051
as played out by Jada
and Jamie right here.

170
00:12:00,553 --> 00:12:04,547
But he can't bring himself
to actually ask her out,

171
00:12:04,641 --> 00:12:07,137
and the way Jamie plays it
and the way Jada plays I,

172
00:12:07,227 --> 00:12:11,516
I, for one, feel Jamie melt
when Jada's eyes look up

173
00:12:11,606 --> 00:12:13,392
at the moment that just passed.

174
00:12:16,277 --> 00:12:21,693
There's this kind of instant regret
at his having failed himself.

175
00:12:27,413 --> 00:12:29,029
And as she's leaving,

176
00:12:29,123 --> 00:12:33,162
she realizes she has no way
to ever have contact with this guy again.

177
00:12:33,253 --> 00:12:35,540
She could take cabs in LA
for the next 15 years

178
00:12:35,630 --> 00:12:39,794
and might not run into him.
So she responds to her impulse

179
00:12:39,884 --> 00:12:43,843
and she gives him her card,
and then the contact is made.

180
00:12:56,401 --> 00:12:58,897
Feeling that she's just been
in this cab with this man

181
00:12:58,987 --> 00:13:01,570
who has other plans in life
beyond driving a cab

182
00:13:01,656 --> 00:13:05,615
but just understood her
and was so generous

183
00:13:05,702 --> 00:13:09,445
about giving up something that's his
because he recognised she needed it.

184
00:13:09,539 --> 00:13:11,780
And it's kind of the rapport and intimacy

185
00:13:11,874 --> 00:13:14,241
that can be struck up
only between strangers,

186
00:13:14,335 --> 00:13:16,872
because you believe
there's no consequence,

187
00:13:16,963 --> 00:13:18,458
"cause you're never gonna
see each other again.

188
00:13:18,548 --> 00:13:19,333
So you can be open.

189
00:13:19,340 --> 00:13:20,290
So you can be open.

190
00:13:24,304 --> 00:13:29,925
Vincent is somebody who is decisive
and who's embraced force

191
00:13:30,018 --> 00:13:31,929
as a way of controlling

192
00:13:32,812 --> 00:13:34,307
his environment, as a way of...

193
00:13:34,397 --> 00:13:37,105
And I don't think Vincent is
actually actively aware of this,

194
00:13:37,191 --> 00:13:40,229
but as a way of
controlling the environment

195
00:13:40,320 --> 00:13:43,153
so that bad things don't happen to him.

196
00:13:43,239 --> 00:13:47,324
He, consequently, is somebody
who can be improvisational.

197
00:13:47,410 --> 00:13:50,402
He's highly trained, he takes action,
he has opinions.

198
00:13:50,496 --> 00:13:52,533
Max is exactly the opposite.

199
00:13:55,460 --> 00:14:00,955
Vincent chooses public transportation,
and the thought behind that

200
00:14:01,049 --> 00:14:03,916
is the same thought
that's behind Vincent's suit.

201
00:14:04,010 --> 00:14:06,547
It serves two purposes.

202
00:14:06,637 --> 00:14:10,301
One is to be indistinguishable,
to be anonymous,

203
00:14:10,391 --> 00:14:12,974
so that if somebody witnesses Vincent

204
00:14:14,395 --> 00:14:17,262
do an illegal act and are later
questioned by the police

205
00:14:17,357 --> 00:14:19,644
and they're trying to describe him,
it's a guy with grey hair,

206
00:14:19,734 --> 00:14:23,648
kind of average-sized, grey suit,
white shirt, there's nothing there.

207
00:14:23,738 --> 00:14:26,150
So that choice is,

208
00:14:26,240 --> 00:14:29,198
in the first instance,
simply really good tradecraft,

209
00:14:29,285 --> 00:14:32,198
to be inconspicuous by being anonymous.

210
00:14:32,288 --> 00:14:35,660
And that's one of the reasons that
he also picks public transportation.

211
00:14:35,750 --> 00:14:38,868
In his mind,
and according to his plan for tonight,

212
00:14:38,961 --> 00:14:40,543
the cab driver who's driving him around

213
00:14:40,630 --> 00:14:45,045
will not, in fact, know what he's doing
at each of the stops he has to make.

214
00:14:45,134 --> 00:14:48,381
This is an interesting shot.
I'm gonna digress here because, again,

215
00:14:48,471 --> 00:14:52,840
this is something only possible
with high-definition video.

216
00:14:52,934 --> 00:14:55,676
It became a whole strategy
about how to see the world

217
00:14:55,770 --> 00:14:59,308
that Vincent and Max
are gonna traverse this night.

218
00:14:59,399 --> 00:15:04,394
I viewed the first scene between Max
and Vincent in the cab as casting.

219
00:15:05,571 --> 00:15:07,733
Vincent is being
provocative intentionally,

220
00:15:07,824 --> 00:15:11,237
saying things about Los Angeles,
"Nobody knows each other,"

221
00:15:11,327 --> 00:15:13,364
to see what Max's reaction is gonna be.

222
00:15:13,454 --> 00:15:17,698
And if Max was aggressively defensive,
Vincent might just have changed cabs.

223
00:15:17,792 --> 00:15:21,877
And when Tom and I
were working in preproduction,

224
00:15:21,963 --> 00:15:26,378
I thought that it was likely
that Vincent, in fact, had a cab

225
00:15:26,467 --> 00:15:27,628
that took him from the airport,

226
00:15:27,718 --> 00:15:31,086
and he didn't like that cab driver
for whatever reason,

227
00:15:31,180 --> 00:15:32,386
and so he switched out

228
00:15:32,473 --> 00:15:35,215
when he went to reconnoitre
Annie's building,

229
00:15:35,309 --> 00:15:38,427
and that Max is, in fact,
his second cab of the night.

230
00:15:38,521 --> 00:15:41,730
Vincent would've been one of these
guys who would've been recruited

231
00:15:41,816 --> 00:15:44,274
in the private sector.
