01:24:53,922 --> 01:24:55,788
for a fraction of a second,

1161
01:24:55,882 --> 01:24:59,876
and he's confused by bad things
that are happening to him.

1162
01:24:59,970 --> 01:25:05,261
And he responds by reassembling
his perspective in reacting

1163
01:25:05,350 --> 01:25:07,808
and acting out with violent aggression.

1164
01:25:07,894 --> 01:25:12,104
Now, the audience may or may not only
get a moment of weakness from him,

1165
01:25:12,190 --> 01:25:16,479
but it was fundamental to me
in my understanding of Vincent's history

1166
01:25:16,570 --> 01:25:21,440
and his character that this, in fact, is
something that's repeated into his life.

1167
01:25:25,662 --> 01:25:28,529
Now, what Jamie was supposed to do was...

1168
01:25:28,624 --> 01:25:31,537
His door was open,
and he was supposed to be

1169
01:25:33,045 --> 01:25:35,127
so distracted by the seemingly eternal

1170
01:25:35,130 --> 01:25:37,167
so distracted by the seemingly eternal

1171
01:25:38,550 --> 01:25:40,791
situation he finds himself in,

1172
01:25:40,886 --> 01:25:42,798
meaning that regardless of what happens,

1173
01:25:42,888 --> 01:25:46,176
he winds up back behind the wheel
on the seat of that cab,

1174
01:25:46,266 --> 01:25:49,258
that he just accelerated forward
without closing the door,

1175
01:25:49,353 --> 01:25:52,471
and the door is to bang
into the parked car.

1176
01:25:52,564 --> 01:25:56,398
That didn't happen. The door closed,
and Jamie just headed for the car.

1177
01:25:56,485 --> 01:26:00,399
We're into something called "Scene 86"

1178
01:26:01,698 --> 01:26:06,784
and it's the big, pivotal scene
in the construction of the story.

1179
01:26:06,870 --> 01:26:09,328
Max has been changed
by a number of things that happen,

1180
01:26:09,414 --> 01:26:13,624
starting with the compression of his life,

1181
01:26:13,710 --> 01:26:16,168
facing death in the form of Felix.

1182
01:26:16,254 --> 01:26:19,337
My direction to Jamie
for that scene was that,

1183
01:26:19,424 --> 01:26:22,588
"You have to feel like you're gonna die.
You're gonna die right now."

1184
01:26:22,678 --> 01:26:25,636
And Max manifested individual action
for the first time,

1185
01:26:25,722 --> 01:26:28,965
which was always there.
It had been latent instead of manifest.

1186
01:26:29,059 --> 01:26:30,053
And in the scene with Felix,

1187
01:26:30,143 --> 01:26:33,181
it took the form
of actually mimicking Vincent's style

1188
01:26:33,271 --> 01:26:35,683
when he talks about / Ching, Darwin.

1189
01:26:35,774 --> 01:26:40,735
But between then, with Felix,
and right now, Max is changed.

1190
01:26:40,821 --> 01:26:45,190
And right now, Max sees
beyond the end of Vincent's gun

1191
01:26:45,283 --> 01:26:47,695
to the man who is there.

1192
01:26:47,786 --> 01:26:49,281
Vincent's repeating a pattern,

1193
01:26:49,371 --> 01:26:52,739
and he again delivers
the kind of facile nihilism

1194
01:26:52,833 --> 01:26:54,665
about the purposelessness of the cosmos.

1195
01:26:54,751 --> 01:26:57,122
"Nothing means anything,
so what difference does it make

1196
01:26:57,212 --> 01:26:59,082
"how many bodies are dropped tonight?"

1197
01:26:59,172 --> 01:27:01,335
This is the third time
we've heard this from Vincent,

1198
01:27:01,425 --> 01:27:05,043
and so there's almost
a kind of a self-directed cynicism.

1199
01:27:05,137 --> 01:27:06,377
He calls it "crap."”

1200
01:27:15,272 --> 01:27:18,981
But this time, Max doesn't buy it.
And Max sees through it.

1201
01:27:44,593 --> 01:27:47,381
Every film seems to have
its pivotal scenes,

1202
01:27:47,471 --> 01:27:52,216
and this is the pivotal scene
of this motion picture.

1203
01:27:52,309 --> 01:27:56,644
Max, for the first time,
is seeing beyond the end of the gun

1204
01:27:56,730 --> 01:27:59,722
and is seeing Vincent for who Vincent is,

1205
01:27:59,816 --> 01:28:01,682
which is damaged goods.

1206
01:28:02,444 --> 01:28:05,857
He experiences a feeling
of an understanding for Vincent,

1207
01:28:05,947 --> 01:28:08,564
and he struggles to put it into words.

1208
01:28:14,206 --> 01:28:15,450
And that struggle is something

1209
01:28:15,540 --> 01:28:20,535
I very much wanted Jamie to live through,

1210
01:28:20,629 --> 01:28:22,711
and that is Vincent's sociopathy,

1211
01:28:22,798 --> 01:28:25,293
that even if you put a gun
to his head and told Vincent,

1212
01:28:25,383 --> 01:28:26,753
"Il have to shoot you
unless you can tell me

1213
01:28:26,843 --> 01:28:27,879
"what somebody over there is feeling,"

1214
01:28:27,969 --> 01:28:30,586
Vincent can't do it.
He isn't capable of empathy.

1215
01:28:30,680 --> 01:28:34,298
He's literally incapable of it,
as if he were handicapped.

1216
01:28:43,109 --> 01:28:47,444
So Max renders a negative judgment
on Vincent.

1217
01:28:47,531 --> 01:28:49,818
He says,
"You are low, my brother. Way low."

1218
01:28:51,868 --> 01:28:54,610
Vincent is actually not impervious,

1219
01:28:54,704 --> 01:28:57,162
he's not the Teflon man
we saw landing at LAX.

1220
01:28:57,249 --> 01:28:59,081
He's injured by this.

1221
01:29:01,419 --> 01:29:05,504
And he assaults Max reactively.

1222
01:29:05,590 --> 01:29:10,960
And it's very personal,
and his intent is to devastate Max

1223
01:29:11,054 --> 01:29:14,467
with a prediction of the purposelessness

1224
01:29:14,558 --> 01:29:16,515
of what Max's life will be,

1225
01:29:16,601 --> 01:29:19,434
almost as if Vincent
is the Ghost of Christmas Future,

1226
01:29:19,521 --> 01:29:24,482
and telling him
that Max's evasion is chronic,

1227
01:29:24,568 --> 01:29:28,027
and he'll never achieve
any of his dreams.

1228
01:29:59,436 --> 01:30:03,896
In this scene right here, I can't fail

1229
01:30:03,982 --> 01:30:08,977
but to have a director's appreciation
for actors,

1230
01:30:09,070 --> 01:30:10,777
"cause fine acting is fine acting,

1231
01:30:10,864 --> 01:30:14,528
and it's not something
directors really do,

1232
01:30:14,618 --> 01:30:16,575
except notable exceptions
like John Huston.

1233
01:30:16,661 --> 01:30:21,371
But we have the highest, at least,
I have the highest regard for it,

1234
01:30:21,458 --> 01:30:25,668
because it is that projection
out onto the end of the limb.

1235
01:30:25,754 --> 01:30:27,165
Or on the wire without a net.

1236
01:30:27,255 --> 01:30:31,874
It's, you know,
going through that ineffable place

1237
01:30:33,261 --> 01:30:37,880
where you're simultaneously in control
and completely uncontrolled,

1238
01:30:37,974 --> 01:30:40,511
living, breathing
and being in the moment.

1239
01:30:40,602 --> 01:30:43,936
And I think that's what Jamie Foxx
and Tom Cruise are doing right here.

1240
01:30:44,022 --> 01:30:50,314
And it never ceases
to be marvelous to me.

1241
01:31:04,417 --> 01:31:07,830
Max has taken what Vincent said earlier
and stood it on its head,

1242
01:31:07,921 --> 01:31:11,915
which is to say that
if existence has no inherent meaning,

1243
01:31:12,008 --> 01:31:16,297
and it's meaningless,
then, in fact, the individual is free

1244
01:31:16,388 --> 01:31:18,383
to put meaning into his life
by his actions.

1245
01:31:18,473 --> 01:31:20,259
And Max takes action.

1246
01:31:34,114 --> 01:31:37,277
Max rebels,
and he's about to destroy what, in fact,

1247
01:31:37,367 --> 01:31:39,449
has imprisoned him for the last 12 years.

1248
01:32:01,141 --> 01:32:04,759
In flipping the cab, I designed the shot

1249
01:32:04,853 --> 01:32:08,141
and how many times I wanted the cab
to flip and how I wanted it to end up.

1250
01:32:08,231 --> 01:32:12,976
And the physics of it
are pretty interesting.

1251
01:32:13,069 --> 01:32:14,439
You weight the cab in certain parts,

1252
01:32:14,529 --> 01:32:17,362
and you lift the back of the cab
with kind of an air mortar.

1253
01:32:17,449 --> 01:32:22,319
And you just actually run the left front
of the cab into a piece of concrete,

1254
01:32:22,412 --> 01:32:25,655
and physics do the rest.

1255
01:32:26,166 --> 01:32:31,206
Joel Kramer, the stunt coordinator,
and the stuntmen who worked on this

1256
01:32:31,296 --> 01:32:34,004
are pretty much able to dump the cab
exactly where we want,

1257
01:32:34,090 --> 01:32:37,082
and we went out to an abandoned airstrip

1258
01:32:37,177 --> 01:32:41,717
and set up this course
with exactly the right distances.

1259
01:32:41,806 --> 01:32:45,390
And the cab dropped
where it was supposed to that day,

1260
01:32:45,477 --> 01:32:48,219
and it also dropped
where it was supposed to this day.

1261
01:32:48,313 --> 01:32:52,728
There were about nine cameras there,
but the key camera is the last one,

1262
01:32:54,736 --> 01:32:57,353
the camera in which the cab
actually comes to a stop,

1263
01:32:57,447 --> 01:33:00,405
after it lifts the front
end of this Pontiac.

1264
01:33:00,492 --> 01:33:04,030
And this is take one.
They just hit it, and they nailed it.

1265
01:33:04,120 --> 01:33:06,737
I've reviewed it on the monitors,

1266
01:33:06,831 --> 01:33:09,119
and because of the higher contrast
on the monitors,

1267
01:33:09,209 --> 01:33:13,373
it made it seem as if the crash
was actually more kinetic than it was.

1268
01:33:13,463 --> 01:33:15,921
And I thought it was too violent.

1269
01:33:16,007 --> 01:33:19,750
So we re-shot it, I think, two more times.

1270
01:33:19,844 --> 01:33:22,256
Didn't need any of it. The first take,

1271
01:33:22,347 --> 01:33:24,679
with the multiple cameras,
is the one we used.

1272
01:33:28,019 --> 01:33:33,435
This is Bob Deamer.
Bob Deamer is an officer in the LAPD.

1273
01:33:33,525 --> 01:33:37,268
And I've gone on a number
of ride-alongs with him,

1274
01:33:37,362 --> 01:33:39,399
in which we've had various adventures.

1275
01:33:39,489 --> 01:33:43,198
And contrary to his appearance here,
he's a very tough cop.

1276
01:33:58,383 --> 01:34:00,715
Jamie's so weary of life with Vincent

1277
01:34:00,802 --> 01:34:03,715
that being taken to LA County Jail
sounds like a good idea.

1278
01:34:07,851 --> 01:34:11,310
This begins a music cue
by James Newton Howard

1279
01:34:11,396 --> 01:34:16,186
that's going to alternate
between orchestral,

1280
01:34:16,276 --> 01:34:19,064
with the horns and low strings,

1281
01:34:19,154 --> 01:34:23,739
meaning cellos, violas,

1282
01:34:23,825 --> 01:34:25,941
double bass

1283
01:34:26,035 --> 01:34:30,495
and a horn section and percussion.

1284
01:34:30,582 --> 01:34:33,244
And it begins here,
and it's an extremely long cue.

1285
01:34:33,334 --> 01:34:36,747
Goes for almost 16 or 17 minutes,
taken in total.

1286
01:34:36,838 --> 01:34:39,956
It was written and composed
as a unified cue.

1287
01:34:40,049 --> 01:34:43,792
And that was
some of the fascinating dynamics

1288
01:34:43,887 --> 01:34:46,595
of the construction of this narrative
for those of us who made the film.

1289
01:34:46,598 --> 01:34:48,635
Of the construction of this narrative
for those of us who made the film.

1290
01:34:48,725 --> 01:34:52,013
Because it's immediate
and because it takes place in 10 hours,

1291
01:34:52,103 --> 01:34:55,221
that means you examine
smaller pieces of time

1292
01:34:55,315 --> 01:34:58,774
under a very powerful microscope,
which means that events

1293
01:34:58,860 --> 01:35:02,694
which normally, in a normal film,
might occupy two and a half minutes,

1294
01:35:02,780 --> 01:35:04,737
in this film occupy five minutes,

1295
01:35:04,824 --> 01:35:08,362
because we examine them
much more closely.

1296
01:35:08,453 --> 01:35:11,199
And so, consequently, music cues
that would be two or three minutes,

1297
01:35:11,289 --> 01:35:13,827
which are more conventional,
become five and six minute cues

1298
01:35:13,917 --> 01:35:17,376
or, in this case, a long cue
becomes a hugely long cue.

1299
01:35:46,699 --> 01:35:51,785
The visualization that you're seeing
in some of these shots of Jamie

1300
01:35:51,871 --> 01:35:55,409
on the rooftop are interesting,
because they would not be possible

1301
01:35:55,500 --> 01:35:58,959
with motion-picture film.
Those buildings are not lit.

1302
01:35:59,671 --> 01:36:02,880
There's, I think,
one parking-structure light

1303
01:36:02,966 --> 01:36:05,549
that's on Jamie, and that's about it.

1304
01:36:18,856 --> 01:36:21,314
If I had shot
on 35 mm motion-picture film,

1305
01:36:21,401 --> 01:36:24,894
I would have had to use
a lot of very powerful lights,

1306
01:36:24,988 --> 01:36:27,025
and then it wouldn't have had
a realistic look.

1307
01:36:27,115 --> 01:36:28,902
It would have looked like
it was, in fact, lit.

1308
01:36:28,992 --> 01:36:31,950
So it was... Cityscapes like this

1309
01:36:32,036 --> 01:36:36,371
are one of the key reasons
I wanted to shoot in high-def video,

1310
01:36:36,457 --> 01:36:40,826
because it revealed the whole world
of the city at night.

1311
01:37:03,026 --> 01:37:06,269
That's also apparent in the scene
when Vincent kicks in the door,

1312
01:37:06,362 --> 01:37:10,856
and you're seeing the detail
of the exterior and the depth of field,

1313
01:37:10,950 --> 01:37:13,112
meaning things in the foreground
are in focus

1314
01:37:13,202 --> 01:37:16,786
and things in the deep background
are also in focus,

1315
01:37:16,873 --> 01:37:18,739
including the distant lights.

1316
01:38:10,843 --> 01:38:14,211
Here's more of the lights
that we're seeing

1317
01:38:14,305 --> 01:38:18,344
only as a courtesy
of high-definition video.

1318
01:38:35,243 --> 01:38:38,952
This shot would also have been
impossible in motion-picture film.

1319
01:38:39,038 --> 01:38:41,905
Max would either be not exposed at all,

1320
01:38:41,999 --> 01:38:44,832
and/or he would not be able
to carry the focus.

1321
01:38:48,131 --> 01:38:51,624
This rooftop that Max is on
was a very, very difficult...

1322
01:38:51,717 --> 01:38:56,302
Probably the most difficult location
for us to get permission to shoot on

1323
01:38:56,389 --> 01:39:00,758
in the city, because it's controlled
by the Secret Service.

1324
01:39:00,852 --> 01:39:04,595
And they use it to park vehicles on
from time to time,

1325
01:39:04,689 --> 01:39:08,728
and they don't want anybody
even remotely near the rooftop.

1326
01:39:08,818 --> 01:39:11,560
And it took a lot of convincing

1327
01:39:11,654 --> 01:39:14,066
and us willing to work
under mass restrictions,

1328
01:39:14,157 --> 01:39:18,526
meaning we shot all of Max's work
in about two hours.

1329
01:39:20,246 --> 01:39:23,455
That's the only way we were able
to get permission to be on this rooftop.

1330
01:39:23,541 --> 01:39:25,953
It's the only exposed
rooftop quite like it

1331
01:39:26,043 --> 01:39:29,456
in downtown Los Angeles,
which was why I needed it.

1332
01:40:10,463 --> 01:40:13,455
The drums were originally heard
in Mozambique.

1333
01:40:13,549 --> 01:40:15,711
In Maputo, Mozambique on AIL.

1334
01:40:15,801 --> 01:40:18,919
When I heard them in Maputo,
I recorded them,

1335
01:40:19,013 --> 01:40:23,849
and then we got Ghanaian drummers,
who happened to be in Los Angeles,

1336
01:40:23,935 --> 01:40:27,803
to go into the third level
of my parking garage.

1337
01:40:27,897 --> 01:40:30,184
It's got a lot of echo in it.

1338
01:40:30,274 --> 01:40:35,485
And we repeated the drumming pattern
I had heard in East Africa

1339
01:40:35,571 --> 01:40:37,528
with drummers
who were mostly from West Africa.

1340
01:40:37,615 --> 01:40:38,985
We call them Ghanaian drums.

1341
01:40:39,075 --> 01:40:42,693
In fact, they're Mozambican drums,
if you like.

1342
01:40:42,787 --> 01:40:44,277
And we sampled those.

1343
01:40:44,372 --> 01:40:47,285
We also repeated it
and did them mostly live.

1344
01:41:28,874 --> 01:41:31,866
This scene,
without being able to use digital video,

1345
01:41:31,961 --> 01:41:34,919
would not even have been able
to have been written, much less shot,

1346
01:41:35,006 --> 01:41:37,714
because you wouldn't even conceive

1347
01:41:37,800 --> 01:41:41,418
of a scene in which characters
are moving around with no lights

1348
01:41:41,512 --> 01:41:44,634
and, in fact, it's only their silhouettes
against the city lights

1349
01:41:44,724 --> 01:41:48,433
and a little bit of bounce that's coming
from the city lights themselves

1350
01:41:48,519 --> 01:41:49,639
that enables you to see them.

1351
01:41:49,729 --> 01:41:52,767
It just would've been
physically impossible to capture it.

1352
01:41:52,857 --> 01:41:54,769
The cameras are seeing more
than the naked eye.

1353
01:41:54,859 --> 01:41:58,227
When we finished some of these shots,
and I said, "Cut,"

1354
01:41:58,321 --> 01:42:00,779
everybody had to stay where they were
until the lights were turned on

1355
01:42:00,865 --> 01:42:04,358
so that people didn't trip and fall
and hurt themselves.

1356
01:42:05,411 --> 01:42:06,822
Max grew up in Ladera Heights,

1357
01:42:06,912 --> 01:42:09,574
Which is a very middle-class section
of Los Angeles.

1358
01:42:09,665 --> 01:42:13,124
And he's never been exposed
to street violence, really, in his life,

1359
01:42:13,210 --> 01:42:16,293
except what he might have seen
as a cab driver.

1360
01:42:18,174 --> 01:42:21,007
So he doesn't know how to shoot
an H&K .45.

1361
01:42:52,875 --> 01:42:56,038
In doing some of the research
about what Vincent would've done

1362
01:42:56,128 --> 01:42:57,835
if he walked in a strange building,

1363
01:42:57,922 --> 01:42:59,788
he would have, first of all,

1364
01:42:59,882 --> 01:43:03,045
acclimated himself
to the ambient noise of the building.

1365
01:43:03,135 --> 01:43:06,173
Buildings heat up during the day
when the sun's out.

1366
01:43:06,263 --> 01:43:08,971
At night, they cool off and they contract,

1367
01:43:09,058 --> 01:43:13,518
and thousands of contractions
throughout the entire structure

1368
01:43:13,604 --> 01:43:15,595
give the building noise.

1369
01:43:19,735 --> 01:43:22,982
And if you're quiet in a building,
and you listen, you could listen to it.

1370
01:43:23,072 --> 01:43:25,404
And the point is
that what Vincent would've been doing

1371
01:43:25,491 --> 01:43:28,734
and what he does here
is that he stops, and he listens.

1372
01:43:28,828 --> 01:43:31,574
And he gets the ambient noise
that's supposed to be there.

1373
01:43:31,664 --> 01:43:32,908
Because what he's really listening for,

1374
01:43:32,998 --> 01:43:34,243
once he understands
what the ambient noise

1375
01:43:34,333 --> 01:43:36,370
that's supposed to be there is,
are the anomalous noises.

1376
01:43:36,460 --> 01:43:41,421
And the anomalous noises
are the sounds of his prey

1377
01:43:41,507 --> 01:43:43,214
and that's Annie.

1378
01:43:49,807 --> 01:43:53,721
And all he's doing when he's static here
is, in fact, listening.

1379
01:43:53,811 --> 01:43:58,271
And he's just almost kind of like a bat,
and he's listening for the sound.

1380
01:43:58,357 --> 01:44:01,475
What he hears are her stockings

1381
01:44:02,653 --> 01:44:03,773
scraping against the carpet

1382
01:44:03,863 --> 01:44:06,696
and her palms
scraping against the carpet,

1383
01:44:06,782 --> 01:44:08,989
and that's how he locates her.

1384
01:45:02,254 --> 01:45:05,497
It wasn't planned
that Vincent fall over the chair,

1385
01:45:05,591 --> 01:45:06,672
but when he did,
it's one of those accidents that I love.

1386
01:45:06,675 --> 01:45:11,966
But when he did,
it's one of those accidents that I love.

1387
01:45:12,056 --> 01:45:14,552
I love it when something happens
that's unexpected.

1388
01:45:14,642 --> 01:45:15,848
It's kind of an anomaly.

1389
01:45:19,772 --> 01:45:20,766
I sometimes ask myself,

1390
01:45:20,856 --> 01:45:24,474
"What are the characteristics
of an event or an activity

1391
01:45:24,568 --> 01:45:26,900
"that are gonna make it simulate
something real

1392
01:45:26,987 --> 01:45:28,819
"or feel to me as if it's real?"

1393
01:45:28,906 --> 01:45:32,615
And it's the things
that don't go exactly according to plan.

1394
01:45:33,244 --> 01:45:35,576
I tend to be attracted to them.

1395
01:45:54,265 --> 01:45:55,721
I was attracted to this location

1396
01:45:55,808 --> 01:45:59,972
among all the different
MTA subway stations in Los Angeles,

1397
01:46:00,062 --> 01:46:03,475
particularly because of the amount
of steel.

1398
01:46:03,566 --> 01:46:07,605
I like the sense that they're running
into some place metallic,

1399
01:46:07,695 --> 01:46:09,811
almost like a metallic tube.

1400
01:46:11,031 --> 01:46:16,242
LA's got a pretty beautiful subway
and public-transportation system.

1401
01:46:16,328 --> 01:46:20,367
And when it travels on the surface
and hits some of the train stops,

1402
01:46:20,457 --> 01:46:24,200
many of them are one-offs.
They're individually architected.

1403
01:46:46,525 --> 01:46:50,109
Vincent is enraged.
He's impossibly formidable.

1404
01:46:51,989 --> 01:46:57,155
Max surprised Vincent
and actually pulled the trigger,

1405
01:46:57,244 --> 01:47:00,862
something that Vincent
thought Max incapable of doing.

1406
01:47:03,626 --> 01:47:07,335
In his clumsy way,
Max has been improvisational,

1407
01:47:07,421 --> 01:47:10,084
which brings it back to a theme
that's actually defined

1408
01:47:10,174 --> 01:47:12,461
in Stuart Beattie's script.

1409
01:47:13,218 --> 01:47:17,507
In the jazz club,
when Vincent talks about improvisation

1410
01:47:18,098 --> 01:47:20,009
and Max is acquiring

1411
01:47:21,018 --> 01:47:23,760
certain characteristics
through the agency now,

1412
01:47:23,854 --> 01:47:28,940
not of the advice of Vincent
but via his conflict with him.

1413
01:47:50,839 --> 01:47:55,333
I didn't desire to ameliorate in any way
Vincent's intent.

1414
01:47:55,427 --> 01:47:57,384
Vincent intends to kill Annie.

1415
01:47:57,471 --> 01:48:01,260
And it was something
that I questioned one or two times

1416
01:48:01,350 --> 01:48:03,345
and came to the conclusion
it has to be what happens.

1417
01:48:03,435 --> 01:48:08,601
This is a spectacular MTA station
right above...

1418
01:48:08,691 --> 01:48:11,308
Right amongst a conjunction
of three freeways.

1419
01:48:11,402 --> 01:48:13,359
It's the Harbor Station.

1420
01:48:49,565 --> 01:48:52,102
This is not a visual effect.
This is shot practically,

1421
01:48:52,192 --> 01:48:56,231
as is all these other shots
of pulling out of the Harbor Station.

1422
01:48:56,321 --> 01:48:58,904
There are some shots
that are gonna be coming up

1423
01:48:58,991 --> 01:49:02,200
in which I chose to shoot green screen,

1424
01:49:02,286 --> 01:49:07,326
meaning that I wanted to be able
to customize the backgrounds

1425
01:49:07,416 --> 01:49:09,623
that were outside the windows.

1426
01:49:11,253 --> 01:49:12,618
Like right here.

1427
01:49:12,713 --> 01:49:15,709
And the reason for it was because
I wanted the graphic pattern

1428
01:49:15,799 --> 01:49:20,714
of particularly those rectangles of light,
which are from parking structures,

1429
01:49:20,804 --> 01:49:23,262
and I wanted them to occur
right at this moment.

1430
01:49:27,978 --> 01:49:31,767
Max has closed his eyes
and simply pulled the trigger,

1431
01:49:31,857 --> 01:49:35,066
expecting to die
after he's forced himself,

1432
01:49:35,152 --> 01:49:37,940
impelled himself to confront Vincent.

1433
01:49:47,039 --> 01:49:50,907
There was a direction here,
the particular attitude

1434
01:49:51,460 --> 01:49:53,417
for Vincent to have as he sat down.

1435
01:49:53,504 --> 01:49:55,745
And the direction was to be irritated.

1436
01:49:55,839 --> 01:49:59,503
As if it was being irritated
at something pedestrian.

1437
01:49:59,593 --> 01:50:04,178
And he's irritated
at the absurd outcome of this gunfight,

1438
01:50:05,140 --> 01:50:07,222
at the whole of this night.

1439
01:50:09,436 --> 01:50:10,767
Particularly about the gunfight.

1440
01:50:10,854 --> 01:50:15,473
If Max hadn't closed his eyes
and just fired chaotically, he'd be dead.

1441
01:51:23,427 --> 01:51:26,135
Vincent's ironically repeated
the same line,

1442
01:51:26,221 --> 01:51:29,259
an anecdote about,
"A guy gets on the MTA, dies,

1443
01:51:29,349 --> 01:51:30,555
"think anybody will notice?"

1444
01:51:30,642 --> 01:51:33,134
But it's not a rhetorical question.

1445
01:51:34,188 --> 01:51:36,020
Vincent is asking,

1446
01:51:36,106 --> 01:51:40,725
"Will anybody note
that once upon a time I was here?"

1447
01:51:40,819 --> 01:51:42,730
And he's sincere.

1448
01:51:42,821 --> 01:51:48,863
All of Vincent's life, who he's been,
and all of Max's life,

1449
01:51:48,952 --> 01:51:51,694
it's all been collapsed
into this one moment.

1450
01:51:51,788 --> 01:51:54,997
Into the events of this one night.

1451
01:51:55,083 --> 01:51:56,869
And the night's over.

